                        <item>
                           <note xml:lang="en">Avraham E. Harkavy (1835–1919) was one of the most important
                Russian Orientalist of the 19th century. He received his doctoral degree in
                1872. During the same year, he was attached to the Ministry of National
                Education. On June 1, 1872, he was commissioned to the Imperial Public
                Library in St. Petersburg to sort and study the manuscripts of the First
                Firkovitch Collection and the Samaritan Collections. The following years,
                Harkavy collaborated with Hermann Strack of Leipzig University in the New
                (Mangup) Synagogue in Chufut-Qal’eh on examining and sorting the manuscripts
                of the Second Firkovitch Collection which was subsequently acquired by the
                Imperial Public Library in 1876. On January 9, 1876, he was appointed a
                librarian there by order of Emperor Alexander II, and made head of the
                Department of Hebrew Books. He was the first curator of the Firkovitch
                collections. His unpublished cataloging of these collections consists of
                slips of paper ("Harkavy cards"), placed together with each manuscript, that
                record his identification of and/or a brief description of that manuscript.
                These slips were the foundation for his handwritten four-volume inventory of
                the Yevr.-Arab. section of the Second Firkovitch Collection. (Daria
                Vasyutinsky Shapira, Early Stages of Research of the Firkowicz Collections
                Manuscripts: The Emergence of Russian Jewish Studies. PhD thesis,
                Beer-Sheva: Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, 2018, pp. 121–182).</note>
                           <persName>Avraham Harkavy</persName>
                           <quote xml:lang="ru">p. 4 / N. 1135 (543) / 
                  58 л. изъ соч. о запрещен. бракахъ / Караима (Солом. Наси?) / поврежд. / I /</quote>
                           <bibl>
